I'm the co-founder and studio director of Co-op.

5
00:00:17,196 --> 00:00:19,558
My background is in cultural analysis and media studies.

6
00:00:19,658 --> 00:00:20,919
That's what I went to school for.

7
00:00:21,520 --> 00:00:25,542
And I worked as an organizer and administrator for a research lab in video games.

8
00:00:25,923 --> 00:00:30,966
So I have a lot of experience with organizations and how to run them smoothly.

9
00:00:30,986 --> 00:00:33,968
I was also a community organizer in Montreal.

10
00:00:34,466 --> 00:00:36,427
where I helped organize the Mount Royal Game Society,

11
00:00:36,447 --> 00:00:38,028
which was one of the biggest indie groups

12
00:00:38,128 --> 00:00:40,290
before we shut it down just this past month.

13
00:00:42,051 --> 00:00:43,392
And basically, I'm self-taught

14
00:00:43,512 --> 00:00:45,853
and I'm just figuring things out like the rest of us.

15
00:00:46,233 --> 00:00:47,914
So I don't have any formal education

16
00:00:47,934 --> 00:00:49,475
or background making games

17
00:00:49,675 --> 00:00:51,637
or running businesses or whatever.

18
00:00:53,958 --> 00:00:56,139
So why this talk?

19
00:00:56,600 --> 00:00:58,841
I think that there's not really a lot of advice

20
00:00:59,001 --> 00:01:01,583
when it comes to how to structure a studio

21
00:01:01,783 --> 00:01:03,544
and how to run a game development team.

22
00:01:03,887 --> 00:01:06,448
There's a lot of advice on how to make video games,

23
00:01:06,608 --> 00:01:09,749
but I think that luck plays such an important part

24
00:01:10,410 --> 00:01:13,931
in making things that there's so many things that you can't

25
00:01:13,951 --> 00:01:14,431
account for.

26
00:01:14,752 --> 00:01:16,052
But one thing that you can account for

27
00:01:16,072 --> 00:01:19,013
is your studio structure and how you run your projects.

28
00:01:19,194 --> 00:01:21,775
And that's actually something you have a practical, hands-on

29
00:01:21,835 --> 00:01:22,875
thing that you can change.

30
00:01:25,416 --> 00:01:27,497
And so this is for people who are interested specifically

31
00:01:27,837 --> 00:01:30,579
in starting a company and starting a studio

32
00:01:30,599 --> 00:01:32,660
to make games commercially and sustainably.

33
00:01:33,974 --> 00:01:37,755
And while I think unionization is an incredibly important goal,

34
00:01:38,176 --> 00:01:40,357
there are other things that can augment that goal

35
00:01:40,437 --> 00:01:41,617
and help us reach that point.

36
00:01:41,817 --> 00:01:45,019
And one of them is in learning about co-ops and starting co-ops.

37
00:01:46,980 --> 00:01:49,401
Also, there are other forms of making games and other structures

38
00:01:49,902 --> 00:01:52,403
that are more loose and fluid that some of these things

39
00:01:52,423 --> 00:01:55,144
that I'm talking about might not be super relevant for.

40
00:01:55,424 --> 00:01:56,865
So just keep that in mind.

41
00:01:57,711 --> 00:02:00,074
So a couple caveats. One of them is survivorship bias.

42
00:02:00,835 --> 00:02:03,377
Something to keep in mind whenever you're hearing a talk by anybody

43
00:02:03,477 --> 00:02:04,539
and anyone's giving you advice,

44
00:02:04,899 --> 00:02:08,463
is that they're giving you a talk from a perspective of surviving and success, maybe,

45
00:02:08,983 --> 00:02:11,866
and that that might not be, like, it might not be the whole story.

46
00:02:12,987 --> 00:02:15,210
Also, there's a whole lot of luck, privilege, and money

47
00:02:15,250 --> 00:02:18,553
that goes into starting any sort of venture like this, like having a studio.

48
00:02:19,120 --> 00:02:21,362
And we were really lucky, we had a lot of privilege,

49
00:02:21,462 --> 00:02:23,743
and we also had money saved up from previous jobs,

50
00:02:23,783 --> 00:02:26,665
or we were able to borrow money from friends and family

51
00:02:26,685 --> 00:02:27,325
and things like that.

52
00:02:27,685 --> 00:02:29,746
And I think that that goes a really, really long way

53
00:02:29,947 --> 00:02:32,048
to becoming sustainable, and it's not really

54
00:02:32,108 --> 00:02:32,828
talked about a lot.

55
00:02:33,849 --> 00:02:34,769
And also experience level.

56
00:02:34,789 --> 00:02:36,951
Like I mentioned, a lot of, like myself personally,

57
00:02:36,971 --> 00:02:39,252
and a lot of people at Co-op didn't make games

58
00:02:39,892 --> 00:02:41,333
before we started the studio,

59
00:02:41,693 --> 00:02:44,195
which means that the kind of advice I'm talking about,

60
00:02:44,235 --> 00:02:45,615
the sort of strategies that we've learned,

61
00:02:45,655 --> 00:02:47,136
are coming from that perspective.

62
00:02:47,196 --> 00:02:48,517
So if you have a more formal.

63
00:02:49,007 --> 00:02:52,389
training or experience or background, your mileage may vary.

64
00:02:54,009 --> 00:02:59,272
So Co-op is a company that we founded in 2012, and just a little bit about it.

65
00:02:59,912 --> 00:03:00,852
We've made a couple games.

66
