We most recently released Nog on PlayStation and iOS.

67
00:03:05,594 --> 00:03:06,435
That's what it looks like.

68
00:03:06,955 --> 00:03:11,617
We also worked with Square Enix Montreal on an expansion for Lara Croft Go called The

69
00:03:11,637 --> 00:03:15,279
Mirror of Spirits where we made an all-new chapter for that game.

70
00:03:16,784 --> 00:03:19,385
We had full creative freedom, did all new art, music, and design,

71
00:03:19,405 --> 00:03:20,745
and it was a really fun project.

72
00:03:21,825 --> 00:03:25,246
And this is a lesser known game of ours called Please Don't Space Dog,

73
00:03:25,626 --> 00:03:29,327
where you pilot a space truck with your dog.

74
00:03:29,907 --> 00:03:33,368
And it was made for the original Oculus developer kit.

75
00:03:33,648 --> 00:03:35,949
And this game actually helped us travel around the world

76
00:03:36,029 --> 00:03:38,769
on the festival circuit and get us in front of a lot of people

77
00:03:39,249 --> 00:03:40,930
and opened up a lot of opportunities for us

78
00:03:40,970 --> 00:03:42,470
that we wouldn't have otherwise had.

79
00:03:42,910 --> 00:03:45,751
And that was just about being in the right place and at the right time.

80
00:03:47,438 --> 00:03:49,179
But also we have a bunch of cancelled projects

81
00:03:49,859 --> 00:03:52,800
that I think were really important in terms of building our visibility

82
00:03:53,080 --> 00:03:55,621
when we were working on them and helped sort of open doors

83
00:03:55,781 --> 00:03:57,242
and teach us a lot about making games.

84
00:03:57,302 --> 00:04:02,203
So projects like Skipping Stones, Red Rover, and Fledge.

85
00:04:04,444 --> 00:04:07,005
We also do contract work, like I mentioned, with Square Enix.

86
00:04:07,025 --> 00:04:09,406
We've worked with Cartoon Network and other companies.

87
00:04:10,406 --> 00:04:11,727
And we also do something called CoLab.

88
00:04:12,248 --> 00:04:15,430
which is a fund that we started where we give people

89
00:04:15,630 --> 00:04:17,671
a couple thousand dollars, like whatever we can afford

90
00:04:17,791 --> 00:04:20,532
at any given time, to work on a one to two month project

91
00:04:20,572 --> 00:04:22,993
out of our office where we give them resources,

92
00:04:23,113 --> 00:04:26,875
help, support, and what I think is really interesting

93
00:04:26,915 --> 00:04:29,996
about Colab is we don't take any ownership over the project

94
00:04:30,036 --> 00:04:32,177
so if the person we're doing a Colab with

95
00:04:32,217 --> 00:04:34,858
decides to release their game for free, that's fine.

96
00:04:34,898 --> 00:04:37,479
If they want to charge money for it, that's fine.

97
00:04:37,520 --> 00:04:38,820
The money's theirs, it's not ours.

98
00:04:39,649 --> 00:04:44,774
It's basically a thing that I wish existed for us when we were getting started as experimental game makers,

99
00:04:44,934 --> 00:04:46,575
and it's something that I think is really important.

100
00:04:47,216 --> 00:04:50,819
And I'm going to talk a little bit more about why you should give away your money if you have it.

101
00:04:52,361 --> 00:04:58,186
This is the first one that we did. It's called Gardenarium by Paloma Dawkins, Kyler, and Yilang Yilang.

102
00:04:58,926 --> 00:05:02,450
And this is Orchids to Dusk by Paul Klara-Sue and Ramzi Khadrubi.

103
00:05:04,604 --> 00:05:07,005
And finally, at Co-op, we've done a lot of workshops,

104
00:05:07,365 --> 00:05:09,306
and we've been involved in the Montreal community

105
00:05:09,346 --> 00:05:09,966
where we're based.

106
00:05:10,606 --> 00:05:11,587
And I think that that's been something

107
00:05:11,607 --> 00:05:12,967
that's been really important for us as well.

108
00:05:14,728 --> 00:05:16,129
So, what is Co-op?

109
00:05:16,909 --> 00:05:19,270
I get a lot of questions if it's like an art collective,

110
00:05:19,330 --> 00:05:21,691
is it a company, is it a workers' Co-op?

111
00:05:22,291 --> 00:05:23,872
And I think this is due to the fact that

112
00:05:25,192 --> 00:05:26,192
when we originally started,

113
00:05:26,232 --> 00:05:28,393
we were really inspired by indie record labels,

114
00:05:28,533 --> 00:05:29,614
like music record labels.

115
00:05:29,714 --> 00:05:31,975
We wanted to start a studio that

116
00:05:32,462 --> 00:05:37,023
kind of envisioned a way of making games where everyone's working on their own projects individually

117
00:05:37,123 --> 00:05:42,766
and they're supported by this umbrella name or this umbrella group called co-op. We found out that

118
00:05:43,806 --> 00:05:47,748
because of not knowing what we were doing that that wasn't really sustainable and we kind of

119
00:05:47,908 --> 00:05:51,589
segued into being a more traditional studio structure where we're working together on

120
00:05:51,689 --> 00:05:56,231
smaller projects instead of everybody working on their own and that was just a thing where we

121
00:05:56,271 --> 00:06:00,933
realized we just didn't know what we were doing and everyone on their own was a recipe for disaster

122
00:06:00,973 --> 00:06:01,233
for us.

123
00:06:01,943 --> 00:06:05,345
So it is a company. It's a federally registered company in Canada,

124
00:06:05,565 --> 00:06:06,906
which gives us access to funding.

125
00:06:07,326 --> 00:06:09,787
It's a for-profit corporation, essentially.

126
00:06:10,387 --> 00:06:12,489
And we're all salaried employees with benefits,

127
00:06:12,709 --> 00:06:17,371
and our goal is to make artsy and experimental games commercially sustainably.

128
00:06:17,891 --> 00:06:21,854
So, most importantly, we're structured as a workers' cooperative.

129
00:06:22,114 --> 00:06:24,675
So we're not actually legally registered as a workers' co-op.

130
00:06:24,835 --> 00:06:27,737
And that's because when we were getting started,

131
00:06:27,757 --> 00:06:29,738
we didn't actually even know about the co-op structure.

132
00:06:30,087 --> 00:06:32,247
The name ended up being a happy coincidence.

133
00:06:33,008 --> 00:06:36,769
And we also wanted to be a corporation

134
00:06:36,809 --> 00:06:39,250
because that gave us access to specific funding in Canada

135
00:06:39,290 --> 00:06:40,611
that's really, really helpful,

136
00:06:40,631 --> 00:06:43,332
that can give you hundreds of thousands of dollars,

137
00:06:43,392 --> 00:06:44,773
potentially, if you can get it.

138
00:06:46,073 --> 00:06:48,294
But one thing that we did after our first year

139
00:06:48,474 --> 00:06:49,975
is decide to restructure the studio

140
00:06:50,075 --> 00:06:51,535
as a workers' co-op internally.

141
00:06:51,575 --> 00:06:54,257
So we changed our bylaws and what that means.

142
00:06:54,877 --> 00:06:57,298
So does anyone here know what a workers' co-op is?

143
00:06:59,739 --> 00:07:00,500
Okay, a couple of hands.

144
00:07:01,920 --> 00:07:06,343
So a workers' co-op is essentially a company that's owned by all the employees.

145
00:07:06,563 --> 00:07:10,365
So everyone who's a full-time employee owns the company at an equal level,

146
00:07:10,505 --> 00:07:12,426
and that's regardless of their financial investment.

147
00:07:12,586 --> 00:07:16,428
So if I put something like $50,000 into the start of the company

148
00:07:16,508 --> 00:07:19,730
and someone put in $100, we still own the same amount of shares.

149
00:07:20,651 --> 00:07:25,173
And what's interesting is a lot of game studios and startups

150
00:07:25,673 --> 00:07:28,075
are actually very similar to co-ops when they just get started.

151
00:07:28,675 --> 00:07:32,457
Because you're just a couple of people, you're all working, you're wearing many hats, you're

152
00:07:32,477 --> 00:07:33,517
sharing responsibility.

153
00:07:34,298 --> 00:07:37,439
But what happens and where they diverge is when it comes to growth.

154
00:07:38,779 --> 00:07:42,941
And I think when growth becomes your goal, you're essentially optimizing for money.

155
00:07:43,241 --> 00:07:43,701
And that's it.

156
00:07:44,182 --> 00:07:47,483
And when you're optimizing for money, it forces a lot of compromises.

157
00:07:47,863 --> 00:07:50,484
And it creates exploitation, even against best interests.

158
00:07:50,924 --> 00:07:52,825
That's just kind of how capitalism works.

159
00:07:53,365 --> 00:07:57,247
So as soon as you start doing things where you have to grow, you're also increasing your

160
00:07:57,327 --> 00:07:57,507
overhead.

161
00:07:57,527 --> 00:07:57,807
And that's it.

162
00:07:58,217 --> 00:08:03,538
significantly. And that means you have to make games that will be able to cover those costs,

163
00:08:03,718 --> 00:08:07,899
and you start to make decisions that I think are exploitative because it's inevitable. You

164
00:08:07,919 --> 00:08:13,941
need to keep the lights on, so you do things that will harm somebody at the end of the day.

165
00:08:14,581 --> 00:08:20,262
So we handle growth by capping it. So we have a rule where we can't grow beyond eight people.

166
00:08:21,762 --> 00:08:26,023
And I think capping growth is one of the best things that you can do in this business because

167
00:08:26,845 --> 00:08:28,066
At the end of the day, it's a numbers game.

168
00:08:28,486 --> 00:08:30,988
And the less people you are, the easier

169
00:08:31,028 --> 00:08:33,030
it is to find a sustainable model for yourself.

170
00:08:34,651 --> 00:08:37,073
And it also means that when you're adding new people,

171
00:08:37,674 --> 00:08:39,135
they are going to become an equal owner.

172
00:08:39,455 --> 00:08:42,118
And that becomes really, I don't know how to manage that

173
00:08:42,178 --> 00:08:42,958
at a certain size.

174
00:08:43,038 --> 00:08:45,280
So staying small and staying sustainable

175
00:08:45,380 --> 00:08:48,803
is really, I think, key to being part of a co-op

176
00:08:48,943 --> 00:08:49,544
in making games.

177
00:08:52,194 --> 00:08:54,055
So what does that actually mean? What does it change?

178
00:08:54,215 --> 00:08:57,536
Like, if everyone in your studio is an owner at an equal level,

179
00:08:57,937 --> 00:09:01,678
regardless of who they are, it changes, I think, number one, responsibility.

180
00:09:02,358 --> 00:09:06,780
People who are owners suddenly have this deeper responsibility

181
00:09:07,060 --> 00:09:12,243
in terms of the long-term investment of the studio, the project, your well-being,

182
00:09:12,263 --> 00:09:16,404
and that impacts their decision-making because they're making decisions in a new way now.

183
00:09:17,969 --> 00:09:20,190
what they want out of making games,

184
00:09:20,250 --> 00:09:21,771
but also what the people around them

185
00:09:21,791 --> 00:09:24,412
that they're sharing in this responsibility need and want.

186
00:09:25,432 --> 00:09:26,333
And it changes money,

187
00:09:27,453 --> 00:09:29,674
because it changes how you decide to split money

188
00:09:29,734 --> 00:09:30,794
and what to do with money.

189
00:09:31,775 --> 00:09:34,216
And that all has an ethical reaction.

190
00:09:35,076 --> 00:09:36,657
And I think those ethical reactions

191
00:09:36,877 --> 00:09:38,817
impact things like crunch,

192
00:09:39,538 --> 00:09:41,659
which I think there's a lot of discussion

193
00:09:41,699 --> 00:09:42,699
about crunch in AAA,

194
00:09:42,739 --> 00:09:44,600
but there's not really a lot of talk about.

195
00:09:45,097 --> 00:09:49,921
things like what smaller businesses do because I think small businesses

196
00:09:50,021 --> 00:09:52,703
are as guilty as big companies in terms of

197
00:09:53,184 --> 00:09:56,827
terrible labor practices. You just don't hear about it because there's no one

198
00:09:56,867 --> 00:09:59,909
reporting on it, right? And you don't hear about it as

199
00:10:00,009 --> 00:10:04,733
often because it flies under the radar. So since no one's reporting on that

200
00:10:04,773 --> 00:10:08,556
stuff, it happens in a completely unregulated, without any

201
00:10:08,616 --> 00:10:12,379
accountability sort of way. But when you have a co-op and you're

202
00:10:12,812 --> 00:10:16,494
and you have things like crunch, you are actually making that decision as a team.

203
00:10:17,174 --> 00:10:19,976
And even if it's the bad decision, at the end of the day,

204
00:10:20,236 --> 00:10:23,817
you are the one who's profiting from that work, not somebody else.

205
00:10:24,198 --> 00:10:28,780
You're not crunching because you have to, and then someone makes money and they can either fire you

206
00:10:29,220 --> 00:10:34,262
or keep you, it doesn't matter. They get to retain whatever the result of your crunch is,

207
00:10:34,522 --> 00:10:38,184
and you just hurt yourself in a really significant way for someone else.

208
00:10:38,384 --> 00:10:39,565
And I think that that's really messed up.

209
00:10:41,018 --> 00:10:43,679
And then profits, you can decide what to do with that as a team.

210
00:10:44,180 --> 00:10:46,961
And in terms of health, I think being in a co-op

211
00:10:47,601 --> 00:10:51,043
is a more emotionally healthy way to make games, because I think making games

212
00:10:51,123 --> 00:10:55,005
actually really sucks and is not a very enjoyable process in a

213
00:10:55,045 --> 00:10:58,627
lot of ways. At least it isn't for me. And so I think

214
00:10:58,667 --> 00:11:01,449
that when you're sharing that responsibility with people on an equal

215
00:11:01,509 --> 00:11:04,490
level, you're able to emotionally be more

216
00:11:05,871 --> 00:11:07,312
cognizant of what's going on.

217
00:11:09,408 --> 00:11:13,210
And something that people ask about is like, well, if everyone's making the decisions together,

218
00:11:13,230 --> 00:11:19,093
how do you handle disagreements? And I think what people need to understand is that just

219
00:11:19,154 --> 00:11:23,436
because you're all owners doesn't mean that you all have to agree on everything that you're

220
00:11:23,456 --> 00:11:27,518
working on. You can have different disciplines and people are trusted to do different things.

221
00:11:27,838 --> 00:11:34,942
But overall, because you're all in it together, you tend to find decision making is geared towards

222
00:11:35,338 --> 00:11:37,299
the best, like what's best for everybody.

223
00:11:37,459 --> 00:11:39,760
And I think everyone kind of agrees on what's best.

224
00:11:39,840 --> 00:11:41,061
So we haven't actually had to deal

225
00:11:41,081 --> 00:11:42,061
with a lot of disagreements.

226
00:11:42,942 --> 00:11:44,403
And also, how do you handle people leaving?

227
00:11:45,063 --> 00:11:46,624
To be honest, I don't know the answer to that

228
00:11:46,744 --> 00:11:49,265
because in the six years that we've started our studio,

229
00:11:49,345 --> 00:11:50,405
no one's left yet.

230
00:11:50,845 --> 00:11:52,286
And I think that that's actually a testament

231
00:11:53,006 --> 00:11:55,568
to the co-op model, that people have this deeper

232
00:11:56,348 --> 00:11:57,889
emotional stake in the company

233
00:11:58,149 --> 00:11:59,369
and in making the games together,

234
00:11:59,809 --> 00:12:01,310
that so far no one's left.

235
00:12:03,485 --> 00:12:07,566
So I want to talk about some survival strategies in relation to being a co-op.

236
00:12:08,086 --> 00:12:10,387
And the first one is the team makeup.

237
00:12:10,687 --> 00:12:13,648
So just like kind of what I was talking about how no one's left yet,

238
00:12:13,748 --> 00:12:16,729
part of that is our personalities and our skill sets.

239
00:12:17,050 --> 00:12:19,430
But I think a really important thing is the aspirations.

240
00:12:20,271 --> 00:12:23,612
And when you're choosing like who to work with and who to start something like this with,

241
00:12:23,912 --> 00:12:26,953
your aspirations are where you see the vision for the team in the studio.

242
00:12:27,513 --> 00:12:28,994
And when you come together on that,

243
00:12:29,174 --> 00:12:32,955
I think it's more important than any sort of like experience that you might have.

244
00:12:33,425 --> 00:12:37,269
I actually think experience is probably the least important thing in making games, because

245
00:12:37,489 --> 00:12:41,073
like I said, making games kind of sucks, so you want to do it with people who are on the

246
00:12:41,113 --> 00:12:41,894
same page as you.

247
00:12:42,855 --> 00:12:47,379
And when you're going into business with them and you're sharing the ownership responsibility,

248
00:12:48,080 --> 00:12:50,422
being on the same vision is the most important thing.

249
00:12:52,664 --> 00:12:56,628
Being involved in the local community actually really enriches and influences the people

250
00:12:56,648 --> 00:12:57,048
around you.

251
00:12:57,168 --> 00:12:57,809
Like just being...

252
00:12:58,436 --> 00:13:02,497
One of few co-ops in Montreal, I think we have a lot of discussions in the local community

253
00:13:02,577 --> 00:13:06,179
about that model and about that structure and why it works for us and that can influence

254
00:13:06,419 --> 00:13:07,759
a new generation of game makers.

255
00:13:08,119 --> 00:13:11,981
I think that there's a lot of intangible benefits that come from being involved in the community

256
00:13:12,021 --> 00:13:16,022
that I can't point to any specific thing and be like, we did this so this made us more

257
00:13:16,062 --> 00:13:17,503
successful or more survivable.

258
00:13:17,823 --> 00:13:20,644
But I think those intangibles are actually really important to our survival.

259
00:13:23,463 --> 00:13:26,906
Something about our team is that we have an art-first approach,

260
00:13:27,166 --> 00:13:30,630
and I think if it all boiled down to one thing, that's the co-op DNA.

261
00:13:31,751 --> 00:13:33,352
Our team is essentially made...

262
00:13:33,653 --> 00:13:35,014
The ownership is a bunch of artists,

263
00:13:35,034 --> 00:13:37,296
and they're in charge of every decision in the studio.

264
00:13:37,756 --> 00:13:40,519
And we make that decision with an eye for surviving and sustainability,

265
00:13:40,799 --> 00:13:42,301
but it is an art-first approach.

266
00:13:43,041 --> 00:13:48,386
And I think that also impacts things like what kind of values we have.

267
00:13:50,401 --> 00:13:54,503
One of the values that we have is valuing production and having a production model.

268
00:13:54,663 --> 00:14:00,627
So for me, as one of the key owners in the studio, I am a full-time producer, essentially.

269
00:14:00,707 --> 00:14:03,389
I don't actually work on the day-to-day making of the games.

270
00:14:03,729 --> 00:14:06,771
I am the producer on all our projects, and I handle the business side of things.

271
00:14:09,292 --> 00:14:13,355
I'm an owner, but I'm doing that makes me really invested in these projects that I'm not

272
00:14:13,575 --> 00:14:18,279
like actually working on in a day-to-day basis. And the fact that my team thinks that I'm important

273
00:14:18,339 --> 00:14:22,982
enough as an outsider almost to the creative process to be involved really means that they

274
00:14:23,062 --> 00:14:28,366
value having someone like me around. And I think that that goes towards creating a really healthy

275
00:14:28,446 --> 00:14:33,009
model of learning how to actually make games and having someone handle all the things that

276
00:14:33,050 --> 00:14:36,592
you don't want to handle when you're worrying about design challenges or whatever.

277
00:14:38,897 --> 00:14:41,659
And one of the things that I think gets tricky when you have a co-op is,

278
00:14:42,079 --> 00:14:45,941
how do you shield a team from bad news or something that's difficult?

279
00:14:46,021 --> 00:14:49,343
Or how do you shoulder responsibility when you're all owners and you're all sharing in that?

280
00:14:49,764 --> 00:14:52,045
And I think I kind of mentioned this a little bit before, but

281
00:14:52,745 --> 00:14:54,667
I think you actually want to silo a little bit.

282
00:14:54,947 --> 00:14:58,669
Like, you kind of just trust people to take care of things that are their domains

283
00:14:58,849 --> 00:15:01,271
and that you don't have to micromanage everything.

284
00:15:01,411 --> 00:15:03,452
So people trust me when it comes to the money.

285
00:15:03,752 --> 00:15:07,615
Everyone has access to our bank account and they can check how much money we have if they want to.

286
00:15:08,132 --> 00:15:09,733
But they just don't, they just ask me,

287
00:15:09,813 --> 00:15:12,474
and they trust me to bring up any issues if they come up.

288
00:15:12,614 --> 00:15:14,454
And I'm not gonna keep anything from anyone

289
00:15:14,534 --> 00:15:17,415
because we're all in it together on an equal level.

290
00:15:17,475 --> 00:15:19,656
So if I think they need to know about something,

291
00:15:19,736 --> 00:15:20,216
I'll tell them.

292
00:15:20,236 --> 00:15:21,857
And if I don't think they need to know about something,

293
00:15:21,997 --> 00:15:24,037
they trust me to just keep that to myself.

294
00:15:24,478 --> 00:15:26,718
And people talk about siloing in a really negative way

295
00:15:26,758 --> 00:15:28,459
because it means it's a breakdown of communication.

296
00:15:28,759 --> 00:15:30,380
But I actually think sharing everything

297
00:15:30,420 --> 00:15:32,760
can sometimes be an unnecessary burden

298
00:15:32,880 --> 00:15:34,701
when people are trying to focus on things

299
00:15:34,741 --> 00:15:36,462
that they need to focus on.

300
00:15:39,070 --> 00:15:45,375
And a practical management tool that I learned from my friend Tanya Short at Kitfox,

301
00:15:45,736 --> 00:15:49,959
and I think that this is a very common tool that I just didn't know because I didn't know what I was doing,

302
00:15:50,860 --> 00:15:54,763
is having bi-weekly check-ins with the team that are one-on-ones.

303
00:15:55,423 --> 00:15:58,626
And I think what's really interesting with that, it's like you just sit down and you talk,

304
00:15:59,126 --> 00:16:02,489
and you're like, how are you doing? How do you feel emotionally right now?

305
00:16:02,549 --> 00:16:04,571
Like, how do you feel about work? What's going on in your life?

306
00:16:05,261 --> 00:16:08,664
Is everything good? Are you happy? Is there something that's making you unhappy?

307
00:16:09,044 --> 00:16:13,627
And can I help with that? And I think what's interesting when we're having that conversation as equals

308
00:16:13,727 --> 00:16:16,789
instead of an employer and employee relationship,

309
00:16:17,950 --> 00:16:20,752
they don't tell me what they think they want me to hear, right?

310
00:16:20,852 --> 00:16:22,754
They tell me the honest truth.

311
00:16:23,114 --> 00:16:27,637
And we can have that kind of discussion as equals, and I think that that really levels the playing field.

312
00:16:28,097 --> 00:16:29,438
And I understand where...

313
00:16:30,188 --> 00:16:32,951
everyone is at and they understand where I'm at on an emotional level.

314
00:16:32,991 --> 00:16:35,153
And I think that that goes such a long way.

315
00:16:35,553 --> 00:16:37,475
Like if I could boil down this whole talk, it's kind of like

316
00:16:37,855 --> 00:16:40,357
be on equal levels and keep in touch on your emotions,

317
00:16:40,417 --> 00:16:41,939
and that's making video games, honestly.

318
00:16:44,341 --> 00:16:46,443
And something that I think is bad advice

319
00:16:46,863 --> 00:16:49,066
that I heard a lot when we were getting started was

320
00:16:49,166 --> 00:16:50,147
just focus on your game.

321
00:16:50,527 --> 00:16:52,068
Don't worry about building a company.

322
00:16:52,609 --> 00:16:52,729
And...

323
00:16:54,255 --> 00:16:55,615
This might be good advice for some people,

324
00:16:55,655 --> 00:16:56,915
but I actually think it's terrible

325
00:16:56,975 --> 00:16:58,656
because it doesn't really prepare you

326
00:16:58,696 --> 00:17:00,316
for a post-ship reality.

327
00:17:01,337 --> 00:17:03,977
And we treat our game development

328
00:17:04,697 --> 00:17:06,818
as if every game that we're going to make

329
00:17:06,898 --> 00:17:08,298
is going to bring in zero revenue.

330
00:17:08,878 --> 00:17:09,979
And that's how I think,

331
00:17:10,659 --> 00:17:12,419
that's one of our most important survival strategies

332
00:17:12,459 --> 00:17:14,140
is like, if we make stuff

333
00:17:14,180 --> 00:17:16,060
and we think it's going to do zero sales,

334
00:17:16,680 --> 00:17:18,661
what do we need to do to stay in business?

335
00:17:19,181 --> 00:17:20,862
And one of those,

336
00:17:20,882 --> 00:17:22,242
and then even if you do think

337
00:17:22,262 --> 00:17:23,202
your game's going to be successful.

338
00:17:23,574 --> 00:17:25,015
depending on the kind of funding you have,

339
00:17:25,235 --> 00:17:27,257
you might not actually see any money anyways

340
00:17:27,377 --> 00:17:29,919
because someone else is recouping from your sales.

341
00:17:30,079 --> 00:17:31,440
So you need to figure something out.

342
00:17:32,040 --> 00:17:34,542
And one of the things that we do is contract work.

343
00:17:35,463 --> 00:17:38,245
And contracts are integral to keeping co-op alive.

344
00:17:38,926 --> 00:17:40,046
But they can also be a trap.

345
00:17:40,727 --> 00:17:41,728
It can be an emotional trap

346
00:17:41,768 --> 00:17:43,549
because sometimes bad contracts happen

347
00:17:43,949 --> 00:17:45,190
and you're stuck working on something

348
00:17:45,230 --> 00:17:46,731
that you really despise or hate,

349
00:17:46,851 --> 00:17:48,052
and that can be really difficult.

350
00:17:48,393 --> 00:17:49,333
But even when it's good,

351
00:17:49,453 --> 00:17:51,195
you can end up in a trap where

352
00:17:52,434 --> 00:17:56,676
You basically do a contract, it pays you fine,

353
00:17:56,896 --> 00:17:58,817
and then you're at the end of it, and you're like,

354
00:17:58,857 --> 00:18:01,659
well, now I need money again, so I need to do another contract,

355
00:18:01,739 --> 00:18:03,100
and you can't break out of that cycle.

356
00:18:03,500 --> 00:18:05,001
And that's something that I've seen happen a lot.

357
00:18:05,541 --> 00:18:10,745
So what we do is we split the studio to do both contracting and original work,

358
00:18:11,145 --> 00:18:11,605
if possible.

359
00:18:12,326 --> 00:18:15,488
And I think that this ties into being a co-op, actually,

360
00:18:15,848 --> 00:18:19,070
and our ownership, because we're not, like,

361
00:18:19,130 --> 00:18:22,092
contracting out a B team to work on contract work.

362
00:18:22,583 --> 00:18:27,385
We're taking the people that we've been working with since the start and are putting them on contracts.

363
00:18:27,645 --> 00:18:30,286
And I think that we trust them to do that.

364
00:18:30,346 --> 00:18:35,628
And we know that that work is feeding into this collective pot that's keeping us all alive.

365
00:18:36,348 --> 00:18:39,049
And what we try to do is when contracts wrap up,

366
00:18:39,329 --> 00:18:43,511
is we switch the team that was working on one contract to then be working on original work,

367
00:18:43,891 --> 00:18:47,652
while the other team that was working on original to take on a contract and sharing that responsibility.

368
00:18:47,972 --> 00:18:49,113
And I think we can only do that.

369
00:18:49,586 --> 00:18:52,928
because we're all on the same level and that we all trust each other.

370
00:18:54,369 --> 00:18:57,591
And it also means that we're getting contract work that's based on

371
00:18:57,891 --> 00:19:01,513
our specific reputation and our specific experience and work,

372
00:19:01,673 --> 00:19:05,795
which is really, really important in terms of getting good contracts.

373
00:19:09,858 --> 00:19:13,239
And finally, I think I want to talk a little bit about money and

374
00:19:13,940 --> 00:19:14,580
how to give it away.

375
00:19:15,090 --> 00:19:21,636
So I think one of the things that we do is we have this approach where we take whatever money we have and we put it into benefits like healthcare.

376
00:19:22,356 --> 00:19:28,921
We do internship and mentorship programs, and we do things like funding for co-op, for colab, sorry.

377
00:19:29,682 --> 00:19:32,704
And honestly, at the end of the day, fuck money.

378
00:19:33,004 --> 00:19:41,751
Because I think, you know, regardless of how much someone invests, it doesn't really matter because money and capitalism change our expectation of how to work with people.

379
00:19:42,952 --> 00:19:44,533
And I think that that change of expectation...

380
00:19:45,040 --> 00:19:49,163
really changes how you, it causes exploitation to happen

381
00:19:49,863 --> 00:19:51,644
because it creates a class system essentially

382
00:19:51,684 --> 00:19:53,445
of who has money and who doesn't.

383
00:19:54,445 --> 00:19:56,807
And I think that when you reconsider

384
00:19:56,847 --> 00:19:57,947
your relationship with money,

385
00:19:58,668 --> 00:20:01,289
you start to reconsider how to have a more ethical

386
00:20:01,329 --> 00:20:03,690
and kinder, sustainable way to think about work

387
00:20:03,830 --> 00:20:04,951
and relationships with people.

388
00:20:05,391 --> 00:20:07,132
And I think that that's a more survivable model

389
00:20:07,693 --> 00:20:11,254
that's more emotionally sustainable in the future.

390
00:20:11,575 --> 00:20:13,816
And so at the end of the day, I say fuck money.

391
00:20:15,161 --> 00:20:15,802
And that's my talk.

392
00:20:35,845 --> 00:20:39,327
I have a big question on how you actually do make the company decisions.

393
00:20:39,427 --> 00:20:44,671
Is it a vote based or it seems like you guys all have roles so maybe there's a specific

394
00:20:44,731 --> 00:20:46,212
role for making the final decision?

395
00:20:47,253 --> 00:20:51,756
Yeah, so the question is like how we actually make decisions on a day to day basis in a

396
00:20:51,816 --> 00:20:53,177
more practical sense, right?

397
00:20:53,457 --> 00:20:56,539
And I think yeah, it is a voting based thing where whenever we have

398
00:20:56,989 --> 00:21:01,133
like whenever we have small decisions that are in my domain or in someone else's domain,

399
00:21:01,153 --> 00:21:03,855
we'll just make the decision and trust. But whenever there's a bigger thing,

400
00:21:04,175 --> 00:21:10,200
we call a team meeting, usually once a week on a Friday or something, and we get some drinks and

401
00:21:10,360 --> 00:21:14,424
have a big meeting for one to two hours and just fill in everyone on what's been going on,

402
00:21:14,824 --> 00:21:20,509
and then put things to a vote. And we do majority vote. And so far, in my experience,

403
00:21:20,769 --> 00:21:22,571
there's almost never been a situation where

404
00:21:23,641 --> 00:21:24,962
We've never had a split decision.

405
00:21:25,482 --> 00:21:27,803
And when there are things that are a bit more contentious,

406
00:21:28,243 --> 00:21:31,084
I'll first have one-on-ones with everybody to talk about things

407
00:21:31,144 --> 00:21:33,985
and then come together and have a team meeting and then just vote.

408
00:21:35,026 --> 00:21:35,306
Thank you.

409
00:21:37,167 --> 00:21:38,727
This was a really great talk. Thank you very much.

410
00:21:39,407 --> 00:21:41,228
I've been actually sort of considering something like this.

411
00:21:41,268 --> 00:21:44,830
I'm in Baltimore and I'm sort of thinking about putting something like this together.

412
00:21:45,390 --> 00:21:48,411
But one question that keeps coming up is how intellectual property works

413
00:21:48,491 --> 00:21:49,812
in a system like this, in a structure like this.

414
00:21:50,392 --> 00:21:52,333
And keeping in mind the sort of the fuck money ethos,

415
00:21:52,533 --> 00:21:52,653
like...

416
00:21:53,437 --> 00:21:56,298
How do people who all own the company deal with,

417
00:21:56,658 --> 00:21:57,959
if one person does eventually leave,

418
00:21:58,659 --> 00:22:02,021
their ownership of that intellectual property once they go?

419
00:22:02,401 --> 00:22:03,762
Yeah, so the question is,

420
00:22:03,882 --> 00:22:05,683
how do you handle intellectual property

421
00:22:05,943 --> 00:22:07,164
when you have this sort of structure

422
00:22:07,184 --> 00:22:08,965
where everyone's sharing responsibility and ownership

423
00:22:09,025 --> 00:22:10,145
and what happens if someone leaves?

424
00:22:10,445 --> 00:22:11,486
I think that's a really great question

425
00:22:11,526 --> 00:22:12,927
and that's something that we've thought about.

426
00:22:13,287 --> 00:22:15,968
And at first we were really attached to the idea

427
00:22:16,008 --> 00:22:18,289
that IP stays with the individual

428
00:22:18,349 --> 00:22:19,590
and is licensed to the company.

429
00:22:20,210 --> 00:22:21,451
And we shifted to a model that,

430
00:22:21,954 --> 00:22:25,395
is different because certain funding actually requires the company to own the IP

431
00:22:25,975 --> 00:22:28,376
to cover some Canadian funding.

432
00:22:29,296 --> 00:22:33,278
So what we've done is, honestly, I think it's kind of an agreement right now that

433
00:22:33,938 --> 00:22:37,800
because of the way our company works, every artist sometimes leads a project.

434
00:22:38,240 --> 00:22:39,221
And it's their baby.

435
00:22:39,981 --> 00:22:43,782
And we all get really invested in that, and we all take on that ownership.

436
00:22:43,802 --> 00:22:47,044
But we know that there's a creative lead for every project.

437
00:22:47,244 --> 00:22:51,025
And at the end of the day, it's their decision what to do whenever there's issues.

438
00:22:51,316 --> 00:22:55,818
And if they were to leave, I don't imagine us ever working on that project,

439
00:22:55,858 --> 00:22:57,538
because it wouldn't feel like it's our own.

440
00:22:57,999 --> 00:23:02,761
And I wouldn't want to make a game on something that I don't feel like I actually own.

441
00:23:02,781 --> 00:23:03,901
Do you know what I mean?

442
00:23:03,921 --> 00:23:04,161
Yeah.

443
00:23:04,361 --> 00:23:04,981
Does that make sense?

444
00:23:05,001 --> 00:23:06,302
Yeah, absolutely. Yep. Thank you.

445
00:23:06,422 --> 00:23:06,642
Thank you.

446
00:23:08,482 --> 00:23:09,463
Hi, thanks for your talk.

447
00:23:10,463 --> 00:23:14,964
So I feel like I might be the only one who thinks this is kind of like an anarchistic model,

448
00:23:16,105 --> 00:23:19,706
but I really, really love it. I was just curious how you kind of

449
00:23:20,826 --> 00:23:23,487
prevent the anarchy, other ways apart from just voting,

450
00:23:24,527 --> 00:23:32,830
from like co-op and anarchy seem to be antithetical to each other. So what are some more examples? And also how

451
00:23:32,870 --> 00:23:36,371
do you make up all those spokes? Like do you have a different type of

452
00:23:36,951 --> 00:23:42,215
Gaming company model wise, if you could break down the roles as well.

453
00:23:42,795 --> 00:23:43,476
Two questions, sorry.

454
00:23:43,636 --> 00:23:48,460
Okay, so I think in terms of how things don't fall apart into lacking structure,

455
00:23:48,480 --> 00:23:52,082
is that I think having a production model is really important.

456
00:23:52,142 --> 00:23:54,724
Being a producer and being like, this is how we structure our days

457
00:23:54,784 --> 00:23:56,966
and this is what we're going to focus on on any given days.

458
00:23:57,566 --> 00:23:59,107
But I think people just kind of...

459
00:23:59,688 --> 00:24:01,209
When I talked about the team fit,

460
00:24:01,489 --> 00:24:04,471
I think we're all kind of people who gel really well together

461
00:24:04,531 --> 00:24:05,812
politically and ideologically.

462
00:24:06,195 --> 00:24:10,197
And so we're all working, we always feel like we're moving together in the same direction.

463
00:24:11,077 --> 00:24:13,418
So I don't know if that really answers that part.

464
00:24:13,459 --> 00:24:14,959
Did you all start out together?

465
00:24:16,020 --> 00:24:18,041
Four of us did. We're now seven people.

466
00:24:18,401 --> 00:24:22,223
And so we started four and we hired over the six years three more people.

467
00:24:22,463 --> 00:24:24,944
Okay, so your hiring process maybe?

468
00:24:25,305 --> 00:24:28,806
Yeah, so for our hiring process it's not like you just get hired and suddenly you're an owner.

469
00:24:28,826 --> 00:24:32,408
There's like a six to twelve month probationary period where...

470
00:24:32,793 --> 00:24:37,334
We often will work with someone, and you hire on their own project, like a small game that's

471
00:24:37,354 --> 00:24:40,714
like a one to two months and just feel out if this makes sense for us.

472
00:24:40,934 --> 00:24:44,395
But also if this makes sense for them, if they want to continue with this sort of model.

473
00:24:44,455 --> 00:24:49,896
And then, depending on how things go, it kind of ramps up in terms of ownership to equal

474
00:24:49,936 --> 00:24:50,176
level.

475
00:24:50,256 --> 00:24:50,856
Okay.

